{"id":"267191993_Recent_Developments_in_Inverse_and_Semi-Inverse_Methods_in_the_Mechanics_of_Continua","abstract":"This chapter focuses on recent developments in inverse and semi-inverse methods in the mechanics of continua. An inverse method can be called an investigation of a partial differential equation of physics, if in it the boundary conditions are not prescribed at the outset. Instead, the solution is defined by the differential equation, and certain additional analytical, geometrical, kinematical, or physical properties of the field. In the semi-inverse method, some of the boundary conditions are prescribed at the outset, whereas others are left open and obtained indirectly through certain simplifying assumptions concerning the properties of the field. A classic example for this is St. Venant's theory of the elastic rod in which only stress systems are considered, which leave the mantle surface of a cylindrical rod free from loads, while the exact distribution of the forces on the two bases is not prescribed in advance. Inverse and semi-inverse investigations have been made in all fields of the mechanics of continua. The variety and volume of the results obtained in the various fields are encouraging. This chapter gives example of the use of inverse methods in fluid dynamics found in Euler's earliest paper on hydrodynamics. It also discusses about flow of a viscous incompressible fluid.","authors":["P.F. Nem√©nyi"],"meta":["December 1951Advances in Applied Mechanics 2","DOI:10.1016/S0065-2156(08)70300-4"],"references":["285028040_Spiralformige_Bewgungen_Zaher_Flussigkeiten","284789910_On_the_uniqueness_of_flows_with_given_streamlines","284238196_Sur_la_propagation_des_ondes","284071960_On_the_flow_patterns_common_to_certain_classes_of_plane_fluid_motions","284049755_Sur_les_lignes_de_tension_principale_dont_une_famille_est_constituee_de_lignes_droites","284037991_Potentialstromungen_mit_konstanter_Geschwindigkeit","284035546_On_the_motion_of_prim_gases","28